Airtime Fairness (802.11 downlink)
==================================

This example demonstrates the downlink form of the 802.11 performance ("rate")
anomaly and how a per-station airtime-fair transmit scheduler at the access point
fixes it.

An access point saturates three wireless clients with downlink UDP traffic (one
flow per client, sourced by a wired server). All links are equally good, but the
AP transmits to sta[0] at 6 Mbps and to sta[1] and sta[2] at 54 Mbps -- the way a
real AP rate-adapts to clients with different link quality (configured statically
here via the per-receiver data-frame rate of RateSelection).

The AP's transmit queue is an AirtimeFairnessQueue (one FIFO sub-queue per client).
The two configurations flip only its fairnessEnabled switch:

  Anomaly     - fairnessEnabled = false: the AP serves each client an equal number
                of FRAMES (round-robin). sta[0]'s 9x-longer frames then dominate the
                airtime and every client collapses to sta[0]'s throughput.

  AirtimeFair - fairnessEnabled = true: the AP gives each client an equal share of
                on-air TIME. The fast clients pack more frames into their slice and
                recover; sta[0] is held to its fair time share.

Typical per-client UDP goodput (measured over the steady-state window):

                   sta[0] (6 Mbps)   sta[1..2] (54 Mbps)   total
  Anomaly              1.77                1.77            5.31 Mbps
  AirtimeFair          0.86                4.01            8.88 Mbps

The fast clients recover (from 1.77 to 4.01 Mbps) and total throughput rises, while
the slow client is capped at its airtime share.

The stations use simplified 802.11 management (Ieee80211MgmtStaSimplified /
Ieee80211MgmtApSimplified): they are treated as associated from the start, with no
scan/authenticate/associate handshake and no beacons, which keeps the example focused
on the transmit scheduling.

Run in the Qtenv GUI to see the built-in visualizers (one IntegratedCanvasVisualizer):
  - per-station downlink throughput above each station (statisticVisualizer);
  - a bar chart above the AP of the PHY data rate it uses towards each station -- the
    per-client rate heterogeneity that drives the anomaly (rateVisualizer);
  - each UdpSink also shows its received-packet count in its own display string.

See also:
  - inet.linklayer.ieee80211.mac.queue.AirtimeFairnessQueue
  - the showcases/wireless/rateanomaly showcase (uplink anomaly + TXOP, and this
    downlink case with documentation and charts)
